# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: beale-number
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] An **aeolipile**, **aeolipyle**, or **eolipile**, also known as a **Hero's** (or **Heron's**) **engine**, is a simple, bladeless radial steam turbine which spins when the central water container is heated.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] Torque is produced by steam jets exiting the turbine.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] The Greek-Egyptian mathematician and engineer Hero of Alexandria described the device in the 1st century CE, and many sources give him the credit for its invention.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] However, at least one source credits Vitruvius as the first to describe this appliance in his *De architectura* (c.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] The aeolipile is considered to be the first recorded steam engine or reaction steam turbine, but it is neither a practical source of power nor a direct predecessor of the type of steam engine invented during the Industrial Revolution.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] The name – derived from the Ancient Greek name Αἴολος and the Latin word *pila* – translates literally to 'the ball of Aeolus', Aeolus being the Greek god of the air and wind.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] Because it applies steam to perform work, an aeolipile (depicted in profile) is used as the symbol for the U.S.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] Navy's Boiler Technician Rate, as it was for the earlier Watertender, Boilermaker, and Boilerman ratings.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] The aeolipile usually consists of a spherical or cylindrical vessel with oppositely bent or curved nozzles projecting outwards.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] When the vessel is pressurised with steam, the gas is expelled out of the nozzles, which generates thrust due to the rocket principle as a consequence of the 2nd and 3rd of Newton's laws of motion.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] When the nozzles, pointing in different directions, produce forces along different lines of action perpendicular to the axis of the bearings, the thrusts combine to result in a rotational moment (mechanical couple), or torque, causing the vessel to spin about its axis.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] Aerodynamic drag and frictional forces in the bearings build up quickly with increasing rotational speed (rpm) and consume the accelerating torque, eventually cancelling it and achieving a steady state speed.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] Typically, and as Hero described the device, the water is heated in a simple boiler which forms part of a stand for the rotating vessel.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] Where this is the case, the boiler is connected to the rotating chamber by a pair of pipes that also serve as the pivots for the chamber.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] Alternatively the rotating chamber may itself serve as the boiler, and this arrangement greatly simplifies the pivot/bearing arrangements, as they then do not need to pass steam.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] This can be seen in the illustration of a classroom model shown here.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] Both Hero and Vitruvius draw on the much earlier work by Ctesibius (285–222 BCE), also known as Ktēsíbios or Tesibius, who was an inventor and mathematician in Alexandria, Ptolemaic Egypt.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] He wrote the first known treatises on the science of compressed air and its uses in pumps.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] It is not known whether the aeolipile was put to any practical use in ancient times, and if it was seen as a pragmatic device, a whimsical novelty, an object of reverence, or some other thing.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] A source described it as a mere curiosity for the ancient Greeks, or a "party trick".
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] Hero's drawing shows a standalone device, and was presumably intended as a "temple wonder", like many of the other devices described in *Pneumatica*.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] Vitruvius, on the other hand, mentions use of the aeolipile for demonstrating the physical properties of the weather.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] This account was preserved by the royal Spanish archives at Simancas.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] It is proposed that de Garay used Hero's aeolipile and combined it with the technology used in Roman boats and late medieval galleys.
[src:beale-number/aeolipile] Here, de Garay's invention introduced an innovation where the aeolipile had practical usage, which was to generate motion to the paddlewheels, demonstrating the feasibility of steam-driven boats.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] In mathematics and statistics, the **arithmetic mean** ( /ˌærɪθˈmɛtɪk/ ⓘ *arr-ith-MET-ik*), **arithmetic average**, or just the *mean* or *average* is the sum of a collection of numbers divided by the count of numbers in the collection.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] The collection is often a set of results from an experiment, an observational study, or a survey.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] The term "arithmetic mean" is preferred in some contexts in mathematics and statistics because it helps to distinguish it from other types of means, such as geometric and harmonic.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] Arithmetic means are also frequently used in economics, anthropology, history, and almost every other academic field to some extent.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] For example, per capita income is the arithmetic average of the income of a nation's population.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] While the arithmetic mean is often used to report central tendencies, it is not a robust statistic: it is greatly influenced by outliers (values much larger or smaller than most others).
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] For skewed distributions, such as the distribution of income for which a few people's incomes are substantially higher than most people's, the arithmetic mean may not coincide with one's notion of "middle".
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] In that case, robust statistics, such as the median, may provide a better description of central tendency.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] The arithmetic mean of a set of observed data is equal to the sum of the numerical values of each observation, divided by the total number of observations.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] If the data set is a statistical population (i.e. consists of every possible observation and not just a subset of them), then the mean of that population is called the *population mean* and denoted by the Greek letter $\mu$ .
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] If the data set is a statistical sample (a subset of the population), it is called the *sample mean* (which for a data set X is denoted as ${\overline {X}}$ ).
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] The arithmetic mean can be similarly defined for vectors in multiple dimensions, not only scalar values; this is often referred to as a centroid.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] More generally, because the arithmetic mean is a convex combination (meaning its coefficients sum to 1 ), it can be defined on a convex space, not only a vector space.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] Statistician Churchill Eisenhart, senior researcher fellow at the U.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] National Bureau of Standards, traced the history of the arithmetic mean in detail.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] In the modern age, it started to be used as a way of combining various observations that should be identical, but were not such as estimates of the direction of magnetic north.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] In 1635, mathematician Henry Gellibrand described as "meane" the midpoint of a lowest and highest number, not quite the arithmetic mean.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] The arithmetic mean has several properties that make it interesting, especially as a measure of central tendency.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] The arithmetic mean differs from the median, which is the value that separates the higher half and lower half of a data set.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] When the values in a data set form an arithmetic progression, the median and arithmetic mean are equal.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] For example, in the data set ${1,2,3,4}$ , both the mean and median are $2.5$ .
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] In other cases, the mean and median can differ significantly.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] For instance, in the data set ${1,2,4,8,16}$ , the arithmetic mean is $6.2$ , while the median is 4 .
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] This occurs because the mean is sensitive to extreme values and may not accurately reflect the central tendency of most data points.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] This distinction has practical implications across different fields.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] For example, since the 1980s, the median income in the United States has increased at a slower rate than the arithmetic mean income.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] Similarly, in climate studies, daily mean temperature distributions tend to approximate a normal distribution, whereas annual or monthly rainfall totals often display a skewed distribution, with some periods having unusually high totals while most have relatively low amounts.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] In such cases, the median can provide a more representative measure of central tendency.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] A weighted average, or weighted mean, is an average in which some data points count more heavily than others in that they are given more weight in the calculation.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] Here the weights, which necessarily sum to one, are ${\frac {2}{3}}$ and ${\frac {1}{3}}$ , the former being twice the latter.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] In calculus, and especially multivariable calculus, the mean of a function is loosely defined as the average value of the function over its domain.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] In this context, the analog of a weighted average, in which there are infinitely many possibilities for the precise value of the variable in each range, is called the *mean of the probability distribution*.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] The most widely encountered probability distribution is called the normal distribution; it has the property that all measures of its central tendency, including not just the mean but also the median mentioned above and the mode (the three Ms), are equal.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] This equality does not hold for other probability distributions, as illustrated for the log-normal distribution here.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] Particular care is needed when using cyclic data, such as phases or angles.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] Taking the arithmetic mean of 1° and 359° yields a result of 180°.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] In this situation, 0° (or 360°) is geometrically a better *average* value: there is lower dispersion about it (the points are both 1° from it and 179° from 180°, the putative average).
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] In general application, such an oversight will lead to the average value artificially moving towards the middle of the numerical range.
[src:beale-number/arithmetic-mean] The arithmetic mean is often denoted by a bar (vinculum or macron), as in ${\bar {x}}$ .
[src:beale-number/beale-number] In mechanical engineering, the **Beale number** is a parameter that characterizes the performance of Stirling engines.
[src:beale-number/beale-number] It is often used to estimate the power output of a Stirling engine design.
[src:beale-number/beale-number] For engines operating with a high temperature differential, typical values for the Beale number are in the range 0.11−0.15; where a larger number indicates higher performance.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] A **Carnot heat engine** is a theoretical heat engine that operates on the Carnot cycle.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The basic model for this engine was developed by French military engineer Nicolas Léonard Sadi Carnot in 1824.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The **Carnot engine** model was graphically expanded by Benoît Paul Émile Clapeyron in 1834 and mathematically explored by Rudolf Clausius in 1857, work that led to the fundamental thermodynamic concept of entropy.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The Carnot engine is the most efficient heat engine which is theoretically possible.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The efficiency depends only upon the absolute temperatures of the hot and cold heat reservoirs between which it operates.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] A heat engine acts by transferring energy from a warm region to a cool region of space and, in the process, converting some of that energy to mechanical work.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The system may be worked upon by an external force, and in the process, it can transfer thermal energy from a cooler system to a warmer one, thereby acting as a refrigerator or heat pump rather than a heat engine.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Every thermodynamic system exists in a particular state.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] A thermodynamic cycle occurs when a system is taken through a series of different states, and finally returned to its initial state.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] In the process of going through this cycle, the system may perform work on its surroundings, thereby acting as a heat engine.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The Carnot engine is a theoretical construct, useful for exploring the efficiency limits of other heat engines.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] An actual Carnot engine, however, would be completely impractical to build.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The Carnot engine was publicized in Sadi Carnot's sole work: *Reflections on the Motive Power of Fire* (1824).
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] A short book addressed to practical engineers in popular language, it has been described as "remarkably accessible to modern readers"; "very clearly written ... [the] mathematical arguments are consigned to footnotes".
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] It is known that Carnot was anxious to be understood by non-specialists.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] "The purpose of *Reflexions* was to bring to public notice the potential of the steam engine for improving the standard of living in France".
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The first useful steam engines were developed in Britain and were typically employed for pumping water out of coal mines.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Since an engine could burn the mine's own coal (including waste coal, which had no commercial value) fuel economy was of little concern.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The incentive to have efficient engines arose in parts of the country where fuel was costly, such as Cornwall.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The mines of Cornwall produced useful metals like tin; but not coal.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The fuel to power their pumping engines had to be imported by sea and was expensive; users were keenly aware that "heat cost money".
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] They sought the engine that did the best "duty'", measured in millions of pounds of water lifted one foot high per bushel of coal burnt.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] A practical business measure, it was a crude indication of the thermodynamic efficiency of an engine.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Cornish engineers were famous for the efficiency of their engines and their achievements were studied avidly, not least in France, where coal was expensive too.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Sadi Carnot's book mentioned three of them by name, Richard Trevithick, Arthur Woolf and Jonathan Hornblower.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Such men developed the Cornish engine in which high pressure steam was cut off early when the piston was at the beginning of its stroke, letting the steam's expansion complete the stroke by itself.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Today it might be called *adiabatic expansion*.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Their ideas were enthusiastically taken up in France, where additionally, scientists and engineers were interested in the theory of steam and other engines.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] In the adjacent diagram, from Carnot's 1824 work, *Reflections on the Motive Power of Fire*, there are "two bodies *A* and *B*, kept each at a constant temperature, that of *A* being higher than that of *B*.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] These two bodies to which we can give, or from which we can remove the heat without causing their temperatures to vary, exercise the functions of two unlimited reservoirs of caloric.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] We will call the first the furnace and the second the refrigerator." Carnot then explains how we can obtain motive power, i.e., "work", by carrying a certain quantity of heat from body *A* to body *B*.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] It also acts as a cooler and hence can also act as a refrigerator.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The previous image shows the original piston-and-cylinder diagram used by Carnot in discussing his ideal engine.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The figure at right shows a block diagram of a generic heat engine, such as the Carnot engine.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] In the diagram, the "working body" (system), a term introduced by Clausius in 1850, can be any fluid or vapor body through which heat *Q* can be introduced or transmitted to produce work.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Carnot had postulated that the fluid body could be any substance capable of expansion, such as vapor of water, vapor of alcohol, vapor of mercury, a permanent gas, air, etc.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Although in those early years, engines came in a number of configurations, typically *Q*H was supplied by a boiler, wherein water was boiled over a furnace; *Q*C was typically removed by a stream of cold flowing water in the form of a condenser located on a separate part of the engine.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The output work, *W*, is transmitted by the movement of the piston as it is used to turn a crank-arm, which in turn was typically used to power a pulley so as to lift water out of flooded salt mines.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Carnot defined work as "weight lifted through a height".
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] **Isentropic (reversible adiabatic) expansion of the gas (isentropic work output).** For this step (B to C) the piston and cylinder are assumed to be thermally insulated, thus they neither gain nor lose heat.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The gas continues to expand, doing work on the surroundings, and losing an equivalent amount of internal energy.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The gas expansion causes it to cool to the "cold" temperature, *T*C.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] **Reversible isothermal compression of the gas at the "cold" temperature, *T*C (isothermal heat rejection)** (C to D).
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] (In magnitude, this is the same amount of entropy absorbed in step 1.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] We can refer to the first law of thermodynamics to explain this behavior: Δ*U*= *W*+*Q* .
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] **Isentropic compression of the gas (isentropic work input)** (D to A).
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Once again the piston and cylinder are assumed to be thermally insulated and the cold temperature reservoir is removed.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] During this step, the surroundings continue to do work to further compress the gas and both the temperature and pressure rise now that the heat sink has been removed.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] This additional work increases the internal energy of the gas, compressing it and causing the temperature to rise to *T*H.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] At this point the gas is in the same state as at the start of step 1.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] A corollary to Carnot's theorem states that: All reversible engines operating between the same heat reservoirs are equally efficient.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] It is easily shown that the efficiency η is maximum when the entire cyclic process is a reversible process.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] This means the total entropy of system and surroundings (the entropies of the hot furnace, the "working fluid" of the heat engine, and the cold sink) remains constant when the "working fluid" completes one cycle and returns to its original state.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Since the "working fluid" comes back to the same state after one cycle, and entropy of the system is a state function, the change in entropy of the "working fluid" system is 0.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Thus, it implies that the total entropy change of the furnace and sink is zero, for the process to be reversible and the efficiency of the engine to be maximum.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] This derivation is carried out in the next section.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The coefficient of performance (COP) of the heat engine is the reciprocal of its efficiency.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] For a real heat engine, the total thermodynamic process is generally irreversible.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The working fluid is brought back to its initial state after one cycle, and thus the change of entropy of the fluid system is 0, but the sum of the entropy changes in the hot and cold reservoir in this one cyclical process is greater than 0.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The internal energy of the fluid is also a state variable, so its total change in one cycle is 0.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] During heat transfer from the hot reservoir at *T*H to the fluid, the fluid would have a slightly lower temperature than *T*H, and the process for the fluid may not necessarily remain isothermal.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Let Δ*S*H be the total entropy change of the fluid in the process of intake of heat.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] where the temperature of the fluid T is always slightly lesser than *T*H, in this process.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] where, during this process of transfer of heat to the cold reservoir, the temperature of the fluid T is always slightly greater than *T*C.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] We have only considered the magnitude of the entropy change here.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] To derive this step needs two adiabatic processes involved to show an isentropic process property for the ratio of the changing volumes of two isothermal processes are equal.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] where $\eta ={\frac {W}{Q_{\text{H}}}}$ is the efficiency of the real engine, and $\eta _{\text{I}}$ is the efficiency of the Carnot engine working between the same two reservoirs at the temperatures $T_{\text{H}}$ and $T_{\text{C}}$ .
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] For the Carnot engine, the entire process is 'reversible', and Equation (**7**) is an equality.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Hence, the efficiency of the real engine is always less than the ideal Carnot engine.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The inequality in Equation (**7**) is essentially the statement of the Clausius theorem.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] According to the second theorem, "The efficiency of the Carnot engine is independent of the nature of the working substance".
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] In 1892 Rudolf Diesel patented an internal combustion engine inspired by the Carnot engine.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Diesel knew a Carnot engine is an ideal that cannot be built, but he thought he had invented a working approximation.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] His principle was unsound, but in his struggle to implement it he developed a practical Diesel engine.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The conceptual problem was how to achieve isothermal expansion in an internal combustion engine, since burning fuel at the highest temperature of the cycle would only raise the temperature further.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Diesel's patented solution was: having achieved the highest temperature just by compressing the air, to add a small amount of fuel at a controlled rate, such that heating caused by burning the fuel would be counteracted by cooling caused by air expansion as the piston moved.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Hence all the heat from the fuel would be transformed into work during the isothermal expansion, as required by Carnot's theorem.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] For the idea to work a small mass of fuel would have to be burnt in a huge mass of air.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Diesel first proposed a working engine that would compress air to 250 atmospheres at 800 °C (1,450 °F), then cycle to one atmosphere at 20 °C (50 °F).
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] However, this was well beyond the technological capabilities of the day, since it implied a compression ratio of 60:1.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Such an engine, if it could have been built, would have had an efficiency of 73%.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Accordingly, Diesel sought to compromise.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] He calculated that, were he to reduce the peak pressure to a less ambitious 90 atmospheres, he would sacrifice only 5% of the thermal efficiency.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Seeking financial support, he published the "Theory and Construction of a Rational Heat Engine to Take the Place of the Steam Engine and All Presently Known Combustion Engines" (1893).
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Endorsed by scientific opinion, including Lord Kelvin, he won the backing of Krupp and Maschinenfabrik Augsburg.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] He clung to the Carnot cycle as a symbol.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] But years of practical work failed to achieve an isothermal combustion engine, nor could have done, since it requires such an enormous quantity of air that it cannot develop enough power to compress it.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Furthermore, controlled fuel injection turned out to be no easy matter.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Even so, the Diesel engine slowly evolved over 25 years to become a practical high-compression air engine, its fuel injected near the end of the compression stroke and ignited by the heat of compression, capable by 1969 of 40% efficiency.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] The Carnot heat engine is, ultimately, a theoretical construct based on an *idealized* thermodynamic system.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] On a practical human-scale level the Carnot cycle has proven a valuable model, as in advancing the development of the diesel engine.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] However, on a macroscopic scale limitations placed by the model's assumptions prove it impractical, and, ultimately, incapable of doing any work.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] As such, per Carnot's theorem, the Carnot engine may be thought as the theoretical limit of macroscopic scale heat engines rather than any practical device that could ever be built.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Such "infinitesimal" requirements as these (and others) cause the Carnot cycle to take an *infinite amount of time*, rendering the production of work impossible.
[src:beale-number/carnot-heat-engine] Other practical requirements that make the Carnot cycle impractical to realize include fine control of the gas, and perfect thermal contact with the surroundings (including high and low temperature reservoirs).
[src:beale-number/centimeters] A **centimetre** (International spelling) or **centimeter** (American English), with SI symbol **cm**, is a unit of length in the International System of Units (SI) equal to one hundredth of a metre, *centi-* being the SI prefix for a factor of ⁠1/100⁠.
[src:beale-number/centimeters] Equivalently, there are 100 centimetres in 1 metre.
[src:beale-number/centimeters] The centimetre is the base unit of length in the now deprecated centimetre–gram–second (CGS) system of units.
[src:beale-number/centimeters] Though for many physical quantities, SI prefixes for factors of 103—like *milli-* and *kilo-*—are often preferred by technicians, the centimetre remains a practical unit of length for many everyday measurements; for instance, human height is commonly measured in centimetres.
[src:beale-number/centimeters] A centimetre is approximately the width of the fingernail of an average adult person.
[src:beale-number/centimeters] One millilitre is defined as one cubic centimetre, under the SI system of units.
[src:beale-number/centimeters] These characters are each equal in size to one Chinese character and are typically used only with East Asian, fixed-width CJK fonts.
[src:beale-number/fluidyne-engine] A **Fluidyne engine** is an alpha or gamma type Stirling engine with one or more liquid pistons.
[src:beale-number/fluidyne-engine] It contains a working gas (often air), and either two liquid pistons or one liquid piston and a displacer.
[src:beale-number/fluidyne-engine] The engine was patented in 1973 by the United Kingdom Atomic Energy Authority.
[src:beale-number/fluidyne-engine] Working gas in the engine is heated, and this causes it to expand and push on the water column.
[src:beale-number/fluidyne-engine] This expansion cools the air which contracts, at the same time being pushed back by the weight of the displaced water column.
[src:beale-number/fluidyne-engine] The U-tube version has no moving parts in the engine other than the water and air, although there are two check valves in the pump.
[src:beale-number/fluidyne-engine] This engine operates at a natural resonance cycle that is "tuned" by adjusting the geometry, generally with a "tuning tube" of water.
[src:beale-number/fluidyne-engine] In the classic configuration, the work produced via the water pistons is integrated with a water pump.
[src:beale-number/fluidyne-engine] The simple pump is external to the engine, and consists of two check valves, one on the intake and one on the outlet.
[src:beale-number/fluidyne-engine] In the engine, the loop of oscillating liquid can be thought of as acting as a displacer piston.
[src:beale-number/fluidyne-engine] The liquid in the single tube extending to the pump acts as the power piston.
[src:beale-number/fluidyne-engine] Traditionally the pump is open to the atmosphere, and the hydraulic head is small, so that the absolute engine pressure is close to atmospheric pressure.
[src:beale-number/fluidyne-engine] The videos show operation of a U-tube type model Fluidyne engine.
[src:beale-number/fluidyne-engine] Hot pipe is heated by a heat gun, and water column oscillation builds up to a steady-state level.
[src:beale-number/fluidyne-engine] Second video shows a detail of the actual water displacement.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] A **gas turbine** is a complete continuous-flow internal combustion engine in which air is compressed, fuel is burned in the compressed air, and the resulting hot gas expands through a turbine.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The turbine drives the compressor and, depending on the design, may also produce thrust, shaft power, or both.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The compressor, combustor, and turbine form the gas generator or core of the engine.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Gas turbines operate on the Brayton cycle and are used in aircraft propulsion, electric power generation, marine propulsion, industrial machinery, pumps, gas compressors, and some land vehicles.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In aircraft, the same basic engine core may be used in turbojets, turbofans, turboprops, and turboshafts.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In industrial and marine service, gas turbines are commonly used as shaft-power engines to drive generators, compressors, pumps, or propellers.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] A gas turbine should not be confused with every turbine driven by hot gas.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In the ideal Brayton cycle, the working fluid undergoes four processes: isentropic compression, constant-pressure heat addition, isentropic expansion, and constant-pressure heat rejection.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] This ideal cycle is used to model gas-turbine engines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In an open-cycle gas turbine, air flows continuously through the compressor, combustor, and turbine; the exhaust is discharged to the surroundings rather than recirculated, so the heat-rejection step is an idealized representation of the exhaust being replaced by fresh intake air.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In a real gas turbine, shaft work supplied to the compressor raises the pressure and temperature of the incoming air.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Heat is then added in the combustor by burning fuel in the compressed air.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The resulting high-temperature gas expands through the turbine, producing work to drive the compressor and, depending on the engine type, additional shaft power or jet thrust.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Real compressors, combustors, and turbines depart from the ideal Brayton cycle because of friction, turbulence, pressure losses, heat transfer, and other irreversible effects.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Air is taken in by a compressor, which may use an axial, centrifugal, mixed-flow, or combined design.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The compressed air is then ducted into the combustor, which may use an annular, can, or can-annular design.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The combustor adds heat to the compressed air by burning fuel in the flow, while part of the compressor air is also used for flame control, dilution, and cooling of combustor and turbine components.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The resulting hot gas expands through the turbine, which extracts work from the flow.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Part of this work drives the compressor; the remaining energy may be used to produce jet thrust, drive a fan, drive a propeller through reduction gearing, or power a rotor, accessory gearbox, industrial load, or electrical generator.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The compressor, combustor, and compressor-driving turbine together form the core of the engine, also known as the gas generator, because their output is hot, high-energy gas.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] If the engine has an additional turbine to drive an industrial generator, helicopter rotor, marine propeller, fan, or other load, a larger share of the flow energy is extracted as shaft work.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In some designs, this turbine is mechanically independent of the gas generator and is then called a free power turbine.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In a turbofan, the turbine extracts additional work to drive the fan, while some remaining exhaust energy may still contribute to jet thrust.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In a turboprop, most of the useful propulsive power is delivered through the propeller; in a typical turboprop engine, the propeller produces roughly 90 percent of the total thrust under sea-level standard-day conditions.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In a turbojet engine, only enough energy is extracted from the flow to drive the compressor and other engine components; the remaining gas energy is accelerated through a nozzle to provide the jet that propels the aircraft.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The smaller the engine, the higher the rotation rate of the shaft must be to attain the required blade tip speed.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Blade-tip speed is one of the factors that affects the pressure ratios that can be obtained by the turbine and the compressor, along with blade aerodynamics, stage count, material limits, and component efficiency.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] These factors affect the maximum power and efficiency that can be obtained by the engine.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] For the tip speed to remain constant, if the diameter of a rotor is reduced by half, the rotational speed must double.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] For example, large jet engines operate around 10,000–25,000 rpm, while micro turbines may spin as fast as 500,000 rpm.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Mechanically, gas turbines *can* be less complex than some reciprocating engines, because a simple gas turbine may have one main rotating assembly, the compressor/shaft/turbine rotor, with other moving parts in the fuel and accessory systems.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] This can reduce manufacturing costs in some cases.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] For instance, costing 10,000 ℛℳ for materials, the Jumo 004 proved cheaper than the Junkers 213 piston engine, which was 35,000 ℛℳ, and needed only 375 hours of lower-skill labor to complete (including manufacture, assembly, and shipping), compared to 1,400 for the BMW 801.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] This, however, came with poor efficiency and reliability in early production turbojets.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The low moving-part count of a simple gas turbine does not necessarily make it easier to manufacture than a simple piston engine.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Gas turbines operate at high rotational speeds and high gas temperatures, and their compressors and turbines require precise blade shapes, small clearances, careful rotor balance, and heat-resistant materials.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] More advanced gas turbines, such as modern turbofan engines or combined-cycle power-plant turbines, may have two or three shafts (spools), many rows of compressor and turbine blades, variable stator vanes, and extensive fuel, oil, air, cooling, and control systems.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] A major advantage of gas-turbine engines, especially in aircraft and other applications requiring high sustained power, is their high power-to-weight ratio.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The Federal Aviation Administration notes that turboprop engines develop more power per pound of weight than reciprocating engines in the 180–350 mph cruise-speed range.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Because significant useful work can be generated by a relatively lightweight engine, gas turbines are well-suited to aircraft that require high power output, high speed, or sustained operation at altitude.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Thrust bearings and journal bearings are a critical part of a design.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] They are hydrodynamic oil bearings or oil-cooled rolling-element bearings.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Foil bearings are used in some small machines such as micro turbines and also have strong potential for use in small gas turbines/auxiliary power units.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] A major challenge facing turbine design, especially turbine blades, is reducing the creep that is induced by the high temperatures and stresses that are experienced during operation.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Higher operating temperatures are continuously sought in order to increase efficiency, but come at the cost of higher creep rates.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Several methods have therefore been employed in an attempt to achieve optimal performance while limiting creep, with the most successful ones being high performance coatings and single crystal superalloys.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] These technologies work by limiting deformation that occurs by mechanisms that can be broadly classified as dislocation glide, dislocation climb and diffusional flow.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Protective coatings provide thermal insulation of the blade and offer oxidation and corrosion resistance.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Thermal barrier coatings (TBCs) are often stabilized zirconium dioxide-based ceramics, and oxidation/corrosion resistant coatings (bond coats) typically consist of aluminides or MCrAlY (where M is typically Fe and/or Cr) alloys.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Using TBCs limits the temperature exposure of the superalloy substrate, thereby decreasing the diffusivity of the active species (typically vacancies) within the alloy and reducing dislocation and vacancy creep.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] It has been found that a coating of 1–200 μm can decrease blade temperatures by up to 200 °C (392 °F).
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Bond coats are directly applied onto the surface of the substrate using pack carburization and serve the dual purpose of providing improved adherence for the TBC and oxidation resistance for the substrate.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The Al from the bond coats forms Al2O3 on the TBC-bond coat interface, which provides the oxidation resistance, but also results in the formation of an undesirable interdiffusion (ID) zone between itself and the substrate..
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The oxidation resistance outweighs the drawbacks associated with the ID zone as it increases the lifetime of the blade and limits the efficiency losses caused by a buildup on the outside of the blades.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Nickel-based superalloys boast improved strength and creep resistance due to their composition and resultant microstructure.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The gamma (γ) FCC nickel is alloyed with aluminum and titanium in order to precipitate a uniform dispersion of the coherent Ni3(Al,Ti) gamma-prime (γ') phases.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The finely dispersed γ' precipitates impede dislocation motion and introduce a threshold stress, increasing the stress required for the onset of creep.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Furthermore, γ' is an ordered L12 phase that makes it harder for dislocations to shear past it.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Further Refractory elements such as rhenium and ruthenium can be added in solid solution to improve creep strength.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The addition of these elements reduces the diffusion of the gamma prime phase, thus preserving the fatigue resistance, strength, and creep resistance.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The development of single-crystal superalloys has led to significant improvements in creep resistance as well.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Due to the lack of grain boundaries, single crystals eliminate Coble creep and consequently deform by fewer modes – decreasing the creep rate.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Although single crystals have lower creep at high temperatures, they have significantly lower yield stresses at room temperature, where strength is determined by the Hall–Petch relationship.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Care needs to be taken in order to optimize the design parameters to limit high-temperature creep while not decreasing low-temperature yield strength.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Airbreathing jet engines are gas turbines optimized to produce thrust from the exhaust gases, or from ducted fans connected to the gas turbines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Jet engines that produce thrust from the direct impulse of exhaust gases are often called turbojets.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] While still in service with many militaries and civilian operators, turbojets have mostly been phased out in favor of the turbofan engine due to the turbojet's low fuel efficiency and high noise.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Those that generate thrust with the addition of a ducted fan are called turbofans or (rarely) fan-jets.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] These engines produce nearly 80% of their thrust by the ducted fan, which can be seen from the front of the engine.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] They come in two types, low-bypass turbofan and high bypass, the difference being the amount of air moved by the fan, called "bypass air".
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] These engines offer the benefit of more thrust without extra fuel consumption.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] A turboprop engine is a turbine engine that drives an aircraft propeller using a reduction gear to translate high turbine section operating speed (often in the 10s of thousands) into low thousands necessary for efficient propeller operation.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The benefit of using the turboprop engine is to take advantage of the turbine engine's high power-to-weight ratio to drive a propeller, thus allowing a more powerful, but also smaller engine to be used.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] While military turboprop engines can vary, in the civilian market there are two primary engines to be found: the Pratt & Whitney Canada PT6, a free-turbine turboshaft engine, and the Honeywell TPE331, a fixed turbine engine (formerly designated as the Garrett AiResearch 331).
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Aeroderivative gas turbines are generally based on existing aircraft gas-turbine engines and are smaller and lighter than industrial gas turbines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Aeroderivatives are used in electrical power generation due to their ability to be shut down and handle load changes more quickly than industrial machines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] They are also used in the marine industry to reduce weight.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Common types include the General Electric LM2500, General Electric LM6000, and aeroderivative versions of the Pratt & Whitney PW4000, Pratt & Whitney FT4 and Rolls-Royce RB211.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Aeroderivatives may also be conversions of operating aircraft engines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] FTAI Aviation in 2026 announced plans to rebuild 100 CFM International CFM56 annually into 25-megawatt power turbines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Increasing numbers of gas turbines are being used or even constructed by amateurs.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In its most straightforward form, these are commercial turbines acquired through military surplus or scrapyard sales, then operated for display as part of the hobby of engine collecting.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In its most extreme form, amateurs have even rebuilt engines beyond professional repair and then used them to compete for the land speed record.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The simplest form of self-constructed gas turbine employs an automotive turbocharger as the core component.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] A combustion chamber is fabricated and plumbed between the compressor and turbine sections.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] More sophisticated turbojets are also built, where their thrust and light weight are sufficient to power large model aircraft.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The Schreckling design constructs the entire engine from raw materials, including the fabrication of a centrifugal compressor wheel from plywood, epoxy and wrapped carbon fibre strands.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Several small companies now manufacture small turbines and parts for the amateur.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Most turbojet-powered model aircraft are now using these commercial and semi-commercial microturbines, rather than a Schreckling-like home-build.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Small gas turbines are used as auxiliary power units (APUs) to supply auxiliary power to larger, mobile machines such as an aircraft, and are a turboshaft design.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Industrial gas turbines differ from aeronautical designs in that the frames, bearings, and blading are of heavier construction.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] They are also much more closely integrated with the devices they power—often an electric generator—and the secondary-energy equipment that is used to recover residual energy (largely heat).
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] They range in size from portable mobile plants to large, complex systems weighing more than a hundred tonnes housed in purpose-built buildings.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] When the gas turbine is used solely for shaft power, its thermal efficiency is about 30%.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] However, it may be cheaper to buy electricity than to generate it.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Therefore, many engines are used in CHP (Combined Heat and Power) configurations that can be small enough to be integrated into portable container configurations.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Gas turbines can be particularly efficient when waste heat from the turbine is recovered by a heat recovery steam generator (HRSG) to power a conventional steam turbine in a combined cycle configuration.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The 605 MW General Electric 9HA achieved a 62.22% efficiency rate with temperatures as high as 1,540 °C (2,800 °F).
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] For 2018, GE offers its 826 MW HA at over 64% efficiency in combined cycle due to advances in additive manufacturing and combustion breakthroughs, up from 63.7% in 2017 orders and on track to achieve 65% by the early 2020s.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In March 2018, GE Power achieved a 63.08% gross efficiency for its 7HA turbine.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Aeroderivative gas turbines can also be used in combined cycles, leading to a higher efficiency, but it will not be as high as a specifically designed industrial gas turbine.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] They can also be run in a cogeneration configuration: the exhaust is used for space or water heating, or drives an absorption chiller for cooling the inlet air and increasing the power output, a technology known as turbine inlet air cooling.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Another significant advantage is their ability to be turned on and off within minutes, supplying power during peak or unscheduled demand.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In areas with a shortage of base-load and load following power plant capacity or with low fuel costs, a gas-turbine power plant may regularly operate most hours of the day.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] A large single-cycle gas turbine typically produces 100 to 400 megawatts of electric power and has 35–40% thermodynamic efficiency.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Industrial gas turbines that are used solely for mechanical drive or used in collaboration with a recovery steam generator differ from power generating sets in that they are often smaller and feature a dual shaft design as opposed to a single shaft.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The power range varies from 1 megawatt up to 50 megawatts.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] These engines are connected directly or via a gearbox to either a pump or compressor assembly.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The majority of installations are used within the oil and gas industries.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Mechanical drive applications increase efficiency by around 2%.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Oil and gas platforms require these engines to drive compressors to inject gas into the wells to force oil up via another bore, or to compress the gas for transportation.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] They are also often used to provide power for the platform.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] These platforms do not need to use the engine in collaboration with a CHP system due to getting the gas at an extremely reduced cost (often free from burn off gas).
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The same companies use pump sets to drive the fluids to land and across pipelines in various intervals.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] One modern development seeks to improve efficiency in another way, by separating the compressor and the turbine with a compressed-air store.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In a conventional turbine, up to half the generated power is used driving the compressor.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In a compressed-air energy storage configuration, power is used to drive the compressor, and the compressed air is released to operate the turbine when required.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Turboshaft engines are used to drive compressors in gas pumping stations and natural gas liquefaction plants.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] They are also used in aviation to power all but the smallest modern helicopters, and function as an auxiliary power unit in large commercial aircraft.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] A primary shaft carries the compressor and its turbine, which, together with a combustor, is called a gas generator.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] A separately spinning power turbine is usually used to drive the rotor on helicopters.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Allowing the gas generator and power turbine/rotor to spin at their own speeds allows more flexibility in their design.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] A typical scale-jet engine, or miniature gas turbine or micro-jet, uses a centrifugal compressor.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The pioneer of modern micro-jets, Kurt Schreckling, produced one of the world's first micro-turbines, the FD3/67.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] This engine can produce up to 22 newtons of thrust and can be built by most mechanically minded people with basic engineering tools, such as a metal lathe.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Evolved from piston engine turbochargers, aircraft APUs or small jet engines, microturbines are 25 to 500 kilowatt turbines the size of a refrigerator.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Microturbines have around 15% efficiencies without a recuperator, or 20 to 30% with one, and they can reach 85% combined thermal–electrical efficiency in cogeneration.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Most gas turbines are internal combustion engines, but it is also possible to manufacture an external combustion gas turbine, which is, effectively, a turbine version of a hot-air engine.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Those systems are usually indicated as EFGT (externally-fired gas turbine) or IFGT (indirectly-fired gas turbine).
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] External combustion has been used for the purpose of using pulverized coal or finely ground biomass (such as sawdust) as a fuel.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In the indirect system, a heat exchanger is used, and only clean air with no combustion products travels through the power turbine.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The thermal efficiency is lower in the indirect type of external combustion; however, the turbine blades are not subjected to combustion products, and much lower quality (and therefore cheaper) fuels are able to be used.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] When external combustion is used, it is possible to use exhaust air from the turbine as the primary combustion air.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] This effectively reduces global heat losses, although heat losses associated with the combustion exhaust remain inevitable.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Closed-cycle gas turbines based on helium or supercritical carbon dioxide also hold promise for use with future high-temperature solar and nuclear power generation.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Gas turbines have been used in some ships, locomotives, tanks, experimental cars, buses, and motorcycles.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In surface vehicles, a gas turbine may be used either as a direct mechanical prime mover or as a generator in a series hybrid or turbine-electric powertrain.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] A key advantage of gas turbines in aircraft—their ability to maintain performance at high altitude compared with piston engines, particularly naturally aspirated ones—is generally irrelevant in surface vehicles.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Their high power-to-weight ratio and compact size can still be useful, especially in military vehicles, marine propulsion, and specialized heavy vehicles.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Gas turbines offer high power from a relatively small and light engine, but they have disadvantages in many road-vehicle applications.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] They are typically less responsive and less efficient than piston engines over the wide range of speeds and loads required in normal driving.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In series hybrid vehicles, these problems are reduced because the turbine can run mainly as a generator at a more efficient operating point, while batteries or ultracapacitors supply transient power demand.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] A continuously variable transmission can also reduce, but not eliminate, the mismatch between turbine operation and road-vehicle drive requirements.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Small gas turbines have historically been more expensive to produce than piston engines, partly because piston engines have been mass-produced in much larger numbers.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Although turbochargers and turbo-compound engines also use exhaust-driven turbines, they are not gas-turbine surface vehicles.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] A turbocharger is an exhaust-driven turbine and compressor used to boost a reciprocating engine, while a turbo-compound engine is a reciprocating engine with power-recovery turbines in its exhaust system.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] A number of experiments have been conducted with gas-turbine-powered automobiles, the largest by Chrysler.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] More recently, there has been some interest in the use of turbine engines for hybrid electric cars.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In 2012 a micro-gas-turbine manufacturer, Bladon Jets, secured investments to develop an Ultra Lightweight Range Extender (ULRE) for electric vehicles.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The first serious investigation of using a gas turbine in cars was in 1946, when two engineers, Robert Kafka and Robert Engerstein of Carney Associates, a New York engineering firm, came up with the concept where a unique compact turbine engine design would provide power for a rear-wheel drive car.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] After an article appeared in *Popular Science*, there was no further work, beyond the paper stage.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Bell and Chief Engineer Maurice Wilks from British car manufacturers Rover unveiled the first car powered with a gas-turbine engine.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The two-seater JET1 had the engine positioned behind the seats, air intake grilles on either side of the car, and exhaust outlets on the top of the tail.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] During tests, the car reached top speeds of 140 km/h (87 mph), at a turbine speed of 50,000 rpm.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] After being shown in the United Kingdom and the United States in 1950, JET1 was further developed, and was subjected to speed trials on the Jabbeke highway in Belgium in June 1952, where it exceeded 240 km/h (150 mph).
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The car ran on petrol, paraffin (kerosene) or diesel oil, but fuel consumption problems proved insurmountable for a production car.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] JET1 is on display at the London Science Museum.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] A French turbine-powered car, the SOCEMA-Grégoire, was displayed at the October 1952 Paris Auto Show.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] It was designed by the French engineer Jean-Albert Grégoire.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The first turbine-powered car built in the US was the GM Firebird I, which began evaluations in 1953.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] While photos of the Firebird, I may suggest that the jet turbine's thrust propelled the car like an aircraft, the turbine actually drove the rear wheels.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The Firebird I was never meant to be a commercial passenger car and was built solely for testing & evaluation as well as public relations purposes.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Additional Firebird concept cars, each powered by gas turbines, were developed for the 1953, 1956, and 1959 Motorama auto shows.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The GM Research gas-turbine engine was also fitted to a series of transit buses, starting with the Turbo-Cruiser I of 1953.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Starting in 1954 with a modified Plymouth, the American car manufacturer Chrysler demonstrated several prototype gas-turbine-powered cars from the early 1950s through the early 1980s.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Chrysler built fifty Chrysler Turbine Cars in 1963 and conducted the only consumer trial of gas turbine-powered cars.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Each of their turbines employed a unique rotating recuperator, referred to as a regenerator that increased efficiency.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In 1954, Fiat unveiled a concept car with a turbine engine, called Fiat Turbina.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] This vehicle, looking like an aircraft with wheels, used a unique combination of both jet thrust and the engine driving the wheels.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Speeds of 282 km/h (175 mph) were claimed.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In the 1960s, Ford and GM were also developing gas-turbine semi-trucks.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Ford displayed the Big Red at the 1964 World's Fair.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] With the trailer, it was 29 m (96 ft) long, 4.0 m (13 ft) high, and painted crimson red.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] It contained the Ford-developed gas-turbine engine, with output power and torque of 450 kW (600 hp) and 1,160 N⋅m (855 lb⋅ft).
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The cab boasted a highway map of the continental U.S., a mini-kitchen, a bathroom, and a TV for the co-driver.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The fate of the truck was unknown for several decades, but it was rediscovered in early 2021 in private hands, having been restored to running order.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The Chevrolet division of GM built the *Turbo Titan* series of concept trucks with turbine motors as analogs of the Firebird concepts, including Turbo Titan I (c.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] 1959, shares GT-304 engine with Firebird II), Turbo Titan II (c.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] 1962, shares GT-305 engine with Firebird III), and Turbo Titan III (1965, GT-309 engine); in addition, the GM Bison gas-turbine truck was shown at the 1964 World's Fair.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Clean Air Act Amendments of 1970, research was funded into developing automotive gas-turbine technology.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Design concepts and vehicles were conducted by Chrysler, General Motors, Ford (in collaboration with AiResearch), and American Motors (in conjunction with Williams Research).
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Long-term tests were conducted to evaluate comparable cost efficiency.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Several AMC Hornets were powered by a small Williams regenerative gas turbine weighing 250 lb (113 kg) and producing 80 hp (60 kW; 81 PS) at 4450 rpm.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In 1982, General Motors used an Oldsmobile Delta 88 powered by a gas turbine using pulverized coal dust.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Toyota demonstrated several gas-turbine-powered concept cars, such as the Century gas-turbine hybrid in 1975, the Sports 800 Gas Turbine Hybrid in 1979 and the GTV in 1985.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The GT24 engine was exhibited in 1977 without a vehicle.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In the early 1990s, Volvo introduced the Volvo ECC which was a gas-turbine-powered hybrid electric vehicle.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In 1993, General Motors developed a gas-turbine-powered EV1 series hybrid—as a prototype of the General Motors EV1.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] A Williams International 40 kW turbine drove an alternator which powered the battery–electric powertrain.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The turbine design included a recuperator.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In 2006, GM went into the EcoJet concept car project with Jay Leno.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] At the 2010 Paris Motor Show Jaguar demonstrated its Jaguar C-X75 concept car.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] This electrically powered supercar has a top speed of 204 mph (328 km/h) and can go from 0 to 62 mph (0 to 100 km/h) in 3.4 seconds.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] It uses lithium-ion batteries to power four electric motors, which combine to produce 780 bhp.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] It will travel 68 miles (109 km) on a single charge of the batteries, and uses a pair of Bladon Micro Gas Turbines to re-charge the batteries extending the range to 560 miles (900 km).
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The first race car (in concept only) fitted with a turbine was in 1955 by a US Air Force group as a hobby project with a turbine loaned them by Boeing and a race car owned by Firestone Tire & Rubber company.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The first race car fitted with a turbine for the goal of actual racing was by Rover and the BRM Formula One team joined forces to produce the Rover-BRM, a gas-turbine-powered coupe, which entered the 1963 24 Hours of Le Mans, driven by Graham Hill and Richie Ginther.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] American Ray Heppenstall joined Howmet Corporation and McKee Engineering together to develop their own gas-turbine sports car in 1968, the Howmet TX, which ran several American and European events, including two wins, and also participated in the 1968 24 Hours of Le Mans.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The cars used Continental gas turbines, which eventually set six FIA land speed records for turbine-powered cars.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The next year the STP Lotus 56 turbine car won the Indianapolis 500 pole position even though new rules restricted the air intake dramatically.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] In 1971 Team Lotus principal Colin Chapman introduced the Lotus 56B F1 car, powered by a Pratt & Whitney STN 6/76 gas turbine.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Chapman had a reputation of building radical championship-winning cars, but had to abandon the project because there were too many problems with turbo lag.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] General Motors fitted the GT-30x series of gas turbines (branded "Whirlfire") to several prototype buses in the 1950s and 1960s, including Turbo-Cruiser I (1953, GT-300); Turbo-Cruiser II (1964, GT-309); Turbo-Cruiser III (1968, GT-309); RTX (1968, GT-309); and RTS 3T (1972).
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The arrival of the Capstone Turbine has led to several hybrid bus designs, starting with HEV-1 by AVS of Chattanooga, Tennessee in 1999, and closely followed by Ebus and ISE Research in California, and DesignLine Corporation in New Zealand (and later the United States).
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] AVS turbine hybrids were plagued with reliability and quality control problems, resulting in liquidation of AVS in 2003.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The most successful design by Designline is now operated in 5 cities in 6 countries, with over 30 buses in operation worldwide, and order for several hundred being delivered to Baltimore, and New York City.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Brescia Italy is using serial hybrid buses powered by microturbines on routes through the historical sections of the city.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The MTT Turbine Superbike appeared in 2000 (hence the designation of Y2K Superbike by MTT) and is the first production motorcycle powered by a turbine engine – specifically, a Rolls-Royce Allison model 250 turboshaft engine, producing about 283 kW (380 bhp).
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Speed-tested to 365 km/h or 227 mph (according to some stories, the testing team ran out of road during the test), it holds the Guinness World Record for most powerful production motorcycle and most expensive production motorcycle, with a price tag of US$185,000.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Several locomotive classes have been powered by gas turbines, the most recent incarnation being Bombardier's JetTrain.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The Third Reich *Wehrmacht Heer*'s development division, the Heereswaffenamt (Army Ordnance Board), studied a number of gas-turbine engine designs for use in tanks starting in mid-1944.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The first gas-turbine engine design intended for use in armored fighting vehicle propulsion, the BMW 003-based GT 101, was meant for installation in the Panther tank.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Towards the end of the war, a Jagdtiger was fitted with one of the aforementioned gas turbines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The second use of a gas turbine in an armored fighting vehicle was in 1954 when a unit, PU2979, specifically developed for tanks by C.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Parsons and Company, was installed and trialed in a British Conqueror tank.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The Stridsvagn 103 was developed in the 1950s and was the first mass-produced main battle tank to use a turbine engine, the Boeing T50.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Since then, gas-turbine engines have been used as auxiliary power units in some tanks and as main powerplants in Soviet/Russian T-80s and U.S.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] They are lighter and smaller than diesel engines at the same sustained power output but the models installed to date are less fuel efficient than the equivalent diesel, especially at idle, requiring more fuel to achieve the same combat range.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Successive models of M1 have addressed this problem with battery packs or secondary generators to power the tank's systems while stationary, saving fuel by reducing the need to idle the main turbine.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] T-80s can mount three large external fuel drums to extend their range.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Russia has stopped production of the T-80 in favor of the diesel-powered T-90 (based on the T-72), while Ukraine has developed the diesel-powered T-80UD and T-84 with nearly the power of the gas-turbine tank.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] This system allows a smaller displacement and lighter engine to be used as the tank's power plant and effectively removes turbo lag.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] This special gas turbine/turbocharger can also work independently from the main engine as an ordinary APU.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] A turbine is theoretically more reliable and easier to maintain than a piston engine since it has a simpler construction with fewer moving parts, but in practice, turbine parts experience a higher wear rate due to their higher working speeds.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] The turbine blades are highly sensitive to dust and fine sand so that in desert operations air filters have to be fitted and changed several times daily.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] An improperly fitted filter, or a bullet or shell fragment that punctures the filter, can damage the engine.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Piston engines (especially if turbocharged) also need well-maintained filters, but they are more resilient if the filter does fail.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p01] Like most modern diesel engines used in tanks, gas turbines are usually multi-fuel engines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Gas turbines are used in many naval vessels, where they are valued for their high power-to-weight ratio and their ships' resulting acceleration and ability to get underway quickly.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The first gas-turbine-powered naval vessel was the Royal Navy's motor gunboat *MGB 2009* (formerly *MGB 509*) converted in 1947.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Metropolitan-Vickers fitted their F2/3 jet engine with a power turbine.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The Steam Gun Boat *Grey Goose* was converted to Rolls-Royce gas turbines in 1952 and operated as such from 1953.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The Bold class Fast Patrol Boats *Bold Pioneer* and *Bold Pathfinder* built in 1953 were the first ships created specifically for gas-turbine propulsion.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The first large-scale, partially gas-turbine powered ships were the Royal Navy's Type 81 (Tribal class) frigates with combined steam and gas powerplants.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The first, HMS *Ashanti* was commissioned in 1961.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The German Navy launched the first *Köln*-class frigate in 1961 with 2 Brown, Boveri & Cie gas turbines in the world's first combined diesel and gas propulsion system.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The Soviet Navy commissioned in 1962 the first of 25 *Kashin*-class destroyer with 4 gas turbines in combined gas and gas propulsion system.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Those ships were the first large ships in the world to be powered solely by gas turbines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The Swedish Navy produced 6 Spica-class torpedo boats between 1966 and 1967 powered by 3 Bristol Siddeley Proteus 1282 turbines, each delivering 3,210 kW (4,300 shp).
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] They were later joined by 12 upgraded Norrköping class ships, still with the same engines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] With their aft torpedo tubes replaced by antishipping missiles they served as missile boats until the last was retired in 2005.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The Finnish Navy commissioned two *Turunmaa*-class corvettes, *Turunmaa* and *Karjala*, in 1968.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] They were equipped with one 16,410 kW (22,000 shp) Rolls-Royce Olympus TM1 gas turbine and three Wärtsilä marine diesels for slower speeds.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] They were the fastest vessels in the Finnish Navy; they regularly achieved speeds of 35 knots, and 37.3 knots during sea trials.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The *Turunmaa*s were decommissioned in 2002.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] *Karjala* is today a museum ship in Turku, and *Turunmaa* serves as a floating machine shop and training ship for Satakunta Polytechnical College.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The next series of major naval vessels were the four Canadian *Iroquois*-class helicopter carrying destroyers first commissioned in 1972.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] They used 2 ft-4 main propulsion engines, 2 ft-12 cruise engines and 3 Solar Saturn 750 kW generators.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The first U.S. gas-turbine powered ship was the U.S.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Coast Guard's *Point Thatcher*, a cutter commissioned in 1961 that was powered by two 750 kW (1,000 shp) turbines utilizing controllable-pitch propellers.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The larger *Hamilton*-class High Endurance Cutters, was the first class of larger cutters to utilize gas turbines, the first of which (USCGC *Hamilton*) was commissioned in 1967.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Navy's *Oliver Hazard Perry*-class frigates, *Spruance* and *Arleigh Burke*-class destroyers, and *Ticonderoga*-class guided missile cruisers.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] USS *Makin Island*, a modified *Wasp*-class amphibious assault ship, is to be the Navy's first amphibious assault ship powered by gas turbines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The marine gas turbine operates in a more corrosive atmosphere due to the presence of sea salt in air and fuel and use of cheaper fuels.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Up to the late 1940s, much of the progress on marine gas turbines all over the world took place in design offices and engine builder's workshops and development work was led by the British Royal Navy and other Navies.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] While interest in the gas turbine for marine purposes, both naval and mercantile, continued to increase, the lack of availability of the results of operating experience on early gas-turbine projects limited the number of new ventures on seagoing commercial vessels being embarked upon.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] In 1951, the diesel–electric oil tanker *Auris*, 12,290 deadweight tonnage (DWT) was used to obtain operating experience with a main propulsion gas turbine under service conditions at sea and so became the first ocean-going merchant ship to be powered by a gas turbine.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Following successful sea trials off the Northumbrian coast, the *Auris* set sail from Hebburn-on-Tyne in October 1951 bound for Port Arthur in the US and then Curaçao in the southern Caribbean returning to Avonmouth after 44 days at sea, successfully completing her historic trans-Atlantic crossing.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] During this time at sea the gas turbine burnt diesel fuel and operated without an involuntary stop or mechanical difficulty of any kind.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] She subsequently visited Swansea, Hull, Rotterdam, Oslo and Southampton covering a total of 13,211 nautical miles.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The *Auris* then had all of its power plants replaced with a 3,910 kW (5,250 shp) directly coupled gas turbine to become the first civilian ship to operate solely on gas-turbine power.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Despite the success of this early experimental voyage the gas turbine did not replace the diesel engine as the propulsion plant for large merchant ships.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] At constant cruising speeds the diesel engine simply had no peer in the vital area of fuel economy.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The gas turbine did have more success in Royal Navy ships and the other naval fleets of the world where sudden and rapid changes of speed are required by warships in action.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The United States Maritime Commission were looking for options to update WWII Liberty ships, and heavy-duty gas turbines were one of those selected.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] In 1956 the *John Sergeant* was lengthened and equipped with a General Electric 4,900 kW (6,600 shp) HD gas turbine with exhaust-gas regeneration, reduction gearing and a variable-pitch propeller.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] It operated for 9,700 hours using residual fuel (Bunker C) for 7,000 hours.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Fuel efficiency was on a par with steam propulsion at 0.318 kg/kW (0.523 lb/hp) per hour, and power output was higher than expected at 5,603 kW (7,514 shp) due to the ambient temperature of the North Sea route being lower than the design temperature of the gas turbine.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] This gave the ship a speed capability of 18 knots, up from 11 knots with the original power plant, and well in excess of the 15 knot targeted.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The ship made its first transatlantic crossing with an average speed of 16.8 knots, in spite of some rough weather along the way.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Suitable Bunker C fuel was only available at limited ports because the quality of the fuel was of a critical nature.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The fuel oil also had to be treated on board to reduce contaminants and this was a labor-intensive process that was not suitable for automation at the time.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Ultimately, the variable-pitch propeller, which was of a new and untested design, ended the trial, as three consecutive annual inspections revealed stress-cracking.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] This did not reflect poorly on the marine-propulsion gas-turbine concept though, and the trial was a success overall.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The success of this trial opened the way for more development by GE on the use of HD gas turbines for marine use with heavy fuels.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The *John Sergeant* was scrapped in 1972 at Portsmouth PA.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Boeing launched its first passenger-carrying waterjet-propelled hydrofoil Boeing 929, in April 1974.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Those ships were powered by two Allison 501-KF gas turbines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Between 1971 and 1981, Seatrain Lines operated a scheduled container service between ports on the eastern seaboard of the United States and ports in northwest Europe across the North Atlantic with four container ships of 26,000 tonnes DWT.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Those ships were powered by twin Pratt & Whitney gas turbines of the FT 4 series.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The four ships in the class were named *Euroliner*, *Eurofreighter*, *Asialiner* and *Asiafreighter*.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Following the dramatic Organization of the Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) price increases of the mid-1970s, operations were constrained by rising fuel costs.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Some modification of the engine systems on those ships was undertaken to permit the burning of a lower grade of fuel (i.e., marine diesel).
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Reduction of fuel costs was successful using a different untested fuel in a marine gas turbine but maintenance costs increased with the fuel change.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] After 1981 the ships were sold and refitted with, what at the time, was more economical diesel-fueled engines but the increased engine size reduced cargo space.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The first passenger ferry to use a gas turbine was the GTS *Finnjet*, built in 1977 and powered by two Pratt & Whitney FT 4C-1 DLF turbines, generating 55,000 kW (74,000 shp) and propelling the ship to a speed of 31 knots.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] However, the Finnjet also illustrated the shortcomings of gas-turbine propulsion in commercial craft, as high fuel prices made operating her unprofitable.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] After four years of service, additional diesel engines were installed on the ship to reduce running costs during the off-season.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The Finnjet was also the first ship with a combined diesel–electric and gas propulsion.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Another example of commercial use of gas turbines in a passenger ship is Stena Line's HSS class fastcraft ferries.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] HSS 1500-class *Stena Explorer*, *Stena Voyager* and *Stena Discovery* vessels use combined gas and gas setups of twin GE LM2500 plus GE LM1600 power for a total of 68,000 kW (91,000 shp).
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The slightly smaller HSS 900-class *Stena Carisma*, uses twin ABB–STAL GT35 turbines rated at 34,000 kW (46,000 shp) gross.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The *Stena Discovery* was withdrawn from service in 2007, another victim of too high fuel costs.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] In July 2000, the *Millennium* became the first cruise ship to be powered by both gas and steam turbines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The ship featured two General Electric LM2500 gas-turbine generators whose exhaust heat was used to operate a steam turbine generator in a COGES (combined gas electric and steam) configuration.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Propulsion was provided by two electrically driven Rolls-Royce Mermaid azimuth pods.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The liner RMS *Queen Mary 2* uses a combined diesel and gas configuration.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] In marine racing applications the 2010 C5000 Mystic catamaran Miss GEICO uses two Lycoming T-55 turbines for its power system.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Gas-turbine technology has steadily advanced since its inception and continues to evolve.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Development is actively producing both smaller gas turbines and more powerful and efficient engines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] These advances allow higher compression ratios and turbine inlet temperatures, more efficient combustion and better cooling of engine parts.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Computational fluid dynamics (CFD) has contributed to substantial improvements in the performance and efficiency of gas-turbine engine components through enhanced understanding of the complex viscous flow and heat transfer phenomena involved.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] For this reason, CFD is one of the key computational tools used in design and development of gas turbine engines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The simple-cycle efficiencies of early gas turbines were practically doubled by incorporating inter-cooling, regeneration (or recuperation), and reheating.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] These improvements, of course, come at the expense of increased initial and operation costs, and they cannot be justified unless the decrease in fuel costs offsets the increase in other costs.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The relatively low fuel prices, the general desire in the industry to minimize installation costs, and the tremendous increase in the simple-cycle efficiency to about 40 percent left little desire for opting for these modifications.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] On the emissions side, the challenge is to increase turbine inlet temperatures while at the same time reducing peak flame temperature in order to achieve lower NOx emissions and meet the latest emission regulations.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] In May 2011, Mitsubishi Heavy Industries achieved a turbine inlet temperature of 1,600 °C (2,900 °F) on a 320 megawatt gas turbine, and 460 MW in gas-turbine combined-cycle power generation applications in which gross thermal efficiency exceeds 60%.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Compliant foil bearings were commercially introduced to gas turbines in the 1990s.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] These can withstand over a hundred thousand start/stop cycles and have eliminated the need for an oil system.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The application of microelectronics and power switching technology have enabled the development of commercially viable electricity generation by microturbines for distribution and vehicle propulsion.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] In 2013, General Electric started the development of the GE9X with a compression ratio of 61:1.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] British, German, other national and international test codes are used to standardize the procedures and definitions used to test gas turbines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] Selection of the test code to be used is an agreement between the purchaser and the manufacturer, and has some significance to the design of the turbine and associated systems.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] In the United States, ASME has produced several performance test codes on gas turbines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] These ASME performance test codes have gained international recognition and acceptance for testing gas turbines.
[src:beale-number/gas-turbine-p02] The single most important and differentiating characteristic of ASME performance test codes, including PTC 22, is that the test uncertainty of the measurement indicates the quality of the test and is not to be used as a commercial tolerance.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] A **heat engine** is a system that transfers thermal energy to do mechanical or electrical work.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] While originally conceived in the context of mechanical energy, the concept of the heat engine has been applied to various other kinds of energy, particularly electrical, since at least the late 19th century.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] The heat engine does this by bringing a working substance from a higher state temperature to a lower state temperature.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] A heat source supplies thermal energy that brings the working substance to the higher temperature state.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] The working substance does work in the working body of the engine while transferring heat to the colder sink until it reaches a lower temperature state.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] During this process some of the thermal energy is converted into work by exploiting the properties of the working substance.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] The working substance can be any system with a non-zero heat capacity, but it usually is a gas or liquid.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] During this process, some heat is normally lost to the surroundings and is not converted to work.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Also, in a mechanical engine, some energy is unusable because of friction and drag.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] In general, an engine is any machine that converts energy to mechanical work.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Heat engines distinguish themselves from other types of engines by the fact that their efficiency is fundamentally limited by Carnot's theorem of thermodynamics.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Since the heat source that supplies thermal energy to the engine can thus be powered by virtually any kind of energy, heat engines cover a wide range of applications.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Heat engines are often confused with the cycles they attempt to implement.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Typically, the term "engine" is used for a physical device and "cycle" for the models; thus, for example, a diesel engine is a machine which implements the Diesel cycle.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] In thermodynamics, heat engines are often modeled using a standard engineering model such as the Otto cycle.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] The theoretical model can be refined and augmented with actual data from an operating engine, using tools such as an indicator diagram.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Since very few actual implementations of heat engines exactly match their underlying thermodynamic cycles, one could say that a thermodynamic cycle is an ideal case of a mechanical engine.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] In any case, fully understanding an engine and its efficiency requires a good understanding of the (possibly simplified or idealised) theoretical model, the practical nuances of an actual mechanical engine and the discrepancies between the two.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] In general terms, the larger the difference in temperature between the hot source and the cold sink, the larger is the potential thermal efficiency of the cycle.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] The maximum theoretical efficiency of a heat engine (which no engine ever attains) is equal to the temperature difference between the hot and cold ends divided by the temperature at the hot end, each expressed in absolute temperature.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] The efficiency of these processes is roughly proportional to the temperature drop across them.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Significant energy may be consumed by auxiliary equipment, such as pumps, which effectively reduces efficiency.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Although some cycles have a typical combustion location (internal or external), they can often be implemented with the other.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] For example, John Ericsson developed an external heated engine running on a cycle very much like the earlier Diesel cycle.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] In addition, externally heated engines can often be implemented in open or closed cycles.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Everyday examples of heat engines include the thermal power station, internal combustion engine, firearms, refrigerators and heat pumps.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Power stations are examples of heat engines run in a forward direction in which heat flows from a hot reservoir and flows into a cool reservoir to produce work as the desired product.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Refrigerators remove heat from within a thermally sealed chamber at low temperature and vent waste heat at a higher temperature to the environment and heat pumps take heat from the low temperature environment and 'vent' it into a thermally sealed chamber (a house) at higher temperature.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] In general heat engines exploit the thermal properties associated with the expansion and compression of gases according to the gas laws or the properties associated with phase changes between gas and liquid states.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Earth's atmosphere and hydrosphere—Earth's heat engine—are coupled processes that constantly even out solar heating imbalances through evaporation of surface water, convection, rainfall, winds and ocean circulation, when distributing heat around the globe.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] A Hadley cell is an example of a heat engine.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] It involves the rising of warm and moist air in the earth's equatorial region and the descent of colder air in the subtropics creating a thermally driven direct circulation, with consequent net production of kinetic energy.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] In phase change cycles and engines, the working fluids are gases and liquids.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] The engine converts the working fluid from a gas to a liquid, from liquid to gas, or both, generating work from the fluid expansion or compression.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] A domestic refrigerator is an example of a heat pump: a heat engine in reverse.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Work is used to create a heat differential.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Many cycles can run in reverse to move heat from the cold side to the hot side, making the cold side cooler and the hot side hotter.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Internal combustion engine versions of these cycles are, by their nature, not reversible.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] The Barton evaporation engine is a heat engine based on a cycle producing power and cooled moist air from the evaporation of water into hot dry air.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Mesoscopic heat engines are nanoscale devices that may serve the goal of processing heat fluxes and perform useful work at small scales.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Potential applications include e.g. electric cooling devices.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] In such mesoscopic heat engines, work per cycle of operation fluctuates due to thermal noise.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] There is exact equality that relates average of exponents of work performed by any heat engine and the heat transfer from the hotter heat bath.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] This relation transforms the Carnot's inequality into exact equality.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] The efficiency of a heat engine relates how much useful work is output for a given amount of heat energy input.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] In other words, a heat engine absorbs heat energy from the high temperature heat source, converting part of it to useful work and giving off the rest as waste heat to the cold temperature heat sink.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] In general, the efficiency of a given heat transfer process is defined by the ratio of "what is taken out" to "what is put in".
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] The efficiency is less than 100% because of the waste heat $Q_{c}<0$ unavoidably lost to the cold sink (and corresponding compression work put in) during the required recompression at the cold temperature before the power stroke of the engine can occur again.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] The *theoretical* maximum efficiency of any heat engine depends only on the temperatures it operates between.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] This efficiency is usually derived using an ideal imaginary heat engine such as the Carnot heat engine, although other engines using different cycles can also attain maximum efficiency.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Note that $\Delta S_{h}$ is positive because isothermal expansion in the power stroke increases the multiplicity of the working fluid while $\Delta S_{c}$ is negative since recompression decreases the multiplicity.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] where $T_{h}$ is the absolute temperature of the hot source and $T_{c}$ that of the cold sink, usually measured in kelvins.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] The reasoning behind this being the **maximal** efficiency goes as follows.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] It is first assumed that if a more efficient heat engine than a Carnot engine is possible, then it could be driven in reverse as a heat pump.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Mathematical analysis can be used to show that this assumed combination would result in a net decrease in entropy.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Since, by the second law of thermodynamics, this is statistically improbable to the point of exclusion, the Carnot efficiency is a theoretical upper bound on the reliable efficiency of *any* thermodynamic cycle.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Empirically, no heat engine has ever been shown to run at a greater efficiency than a Carnot cycle heat engine.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Figure 2 and Figure 3 show variations on Carnot cycle efficiency with temperature.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Figure 2 indicates how efficiency changes with an increase in the heat addition temperature for a constant compressor inlet temperature.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Figure 3 indicates how the efficiency changes with an increase in the heat rejection temperature for a constant turbine inlet temperature.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] By its nature, any maximally efficient Carnot cycle must operate at an infinitesimal temperature gradient; this is because any transfer of heat between two bodies of differing temperatures is irreversible, therefore the Carnot efficiency expression applies only to the infinitesimal limit.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] The major problem is that the objective of most heat-engines is to output power, and infinitesimal power is seldom desired.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] A different measure of ideal heat-engine efficiency is given by considerations of endoreversible thermodynamics, where the system is broken into reversible subsystems, but with non reversible interactions between them.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] A classical example is the Curzon–Ahlborn engine, very similar to a Carnot engine, but where the thermal reservoirs at temperature $T_{h}$ and $T_{c}$ are allowed to be different from the temperatures of the substance going through the reversible Carnot cycle: $T'_{h}$ and $T'_{c}$ .
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] The heat transfers between the reservoirs and the substance are considered as conductive (and irreversible) in the form $dQ_{h,c}/dt=\alpha (T_{h,c}-T'_{h,c})$ .
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] In this case, a tradeoff has to be made between power output and efficiency.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] If the engine is operated very slowly, the heat flux is low, $T\approx T'$ and the classical Carnot result is found $\eta =1-{\frac {T_{c}}{T_{h}}},$ but at the price of a vanishing power output.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] As shown, the Curzon–Ahlborn efficiency much more closely models that observed.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Heat engines have been known since antiquity but were only made into useful devices at the time of the industrial revolution in the 18th century.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Engineers have studied the various heat-engine cycles to improve the amount of usable work they could extract from a given power source.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Exploit the physical properties of the working fluid.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] The most common such exploitation is the use of water above the critical point (supercritical water).
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] A newer and very promising material for such applications is supercritical CO2.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] SO2 and xenon have also been considered for such applications.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Downsides include issues of corrosion and erosion, the different chemical behavior above and below the critical point, the needed high pressures and – in the case of sulfur dioxide and to a lesser extent carbon dioxide – toxicity.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Among the mentioned compounds xenon is least suitable for use in a nuclear reactor due to the high neutron absorption cross section of almost all isotopes of xenon, whereas carbon dioxide and water can also double as a neutron moderator for a thermal spectrum reactor.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Exploit the chemical properties of the working fluid.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] A fairly new and novel exploit is to use exotic working fluids with advantageous chemical properties.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] One such is nitrogen dioxide (NO2), a toxic component of smog, which has a natural dimer as di-nitrogen tetraoxide (N2O4).
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] At low temperature, the N2O4 is compressed and then heated.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] The increasing temperature causes each N2O4 to break apart into two NO2 molecules.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] This lowers the molecular weight of the working fluid, which drastically increases the efficiency of the cycle.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Once the NO2 has expanded through the turbine, it is cooled by the heat sink, which makes it recombine into N2O4.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] This is then fed back by the compressor for another cycle.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] Such species as aluminium bromide (Al2Br6), NOCl, and Ga2I6 have all been investigated for such uses.
[src:beale-number/heat-engine] To date, their drawbacks have not warranted their use, despite the efficiency gains that can be realized.
